WEBVTT

00:03.642 --> 00:13.133
[SPEAKER_01]: I do this now because I might forget to tell you because it shows what a great man this guy was and yet how almost tragic it was.

00:13.214 --> 00:17.358
[SPEAKER_01]: Dr. Jack Miller, senior year.

00:17.819 --> 00:22.465
[SPEAKER_01]: We started in a seminar.

00:22.905 --> 00:28.272
[SPEAKER_01]: This was a seminar and I do not remember the teacher's name who started.

00:28.292 --> 00:30.274
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I do too, Schuster.

00:31.520 --> 00:41.690
[SPEAKER_01]: Mr. Schuster, started this seminar and he left and Dr. Miller took it over.

00:41.970 --> 00:48.216
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, when we started it, our grades were going to be based on attendance.

00:49.678 --> 00:59.147
[SPEAKER_01]: Plus, we would have a group of, say, about four or five of us would be responsible for one of the seminar programs.

00:59.267 --> 01:00.328
[SPEAKER_01]: And if it was a good one,

01:01.186 --> 01:03.490
[SPEAKER_01]: That plus your attendance determined you're great.

01:03.510 --> 01:04.432
[SPEAKER_01]: That's what we were told.

01:06.075 --> 01:09.621
[SPEAKER_01]: So we had an exceptionally good one, and my attendance was perfect.

01:10.863 --> 01:13.508
[SPEAKER_01]: It's just one session a week.

01:15.171 --> 01:17.294
[SPEAKER_01]: But Dr. Miller came in just before the course was over.

01:17.675 --> 01:18.857
[SPEAKER_01]: He assigned us an essay.

01:20.778 --> 01:35.337
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I knew I had an A in the course, so my essay was not really top flight at any stretch of the imagination, something offbeat and hurried up and just about to graduate.

01:36.799 --> 01:48.675
[SPEAKER_01]: So I whipped by the animal science deal when this all grades in and I had a D posted for this seminar.

01:50.275 --> 01:52.077
[SPEAKER_01]: So I went in to see Dr. Miller.

01:52.137 --> 01:59.667
[SPEAKER_01]: I knew he'd made a mistake, and I said, Dr. Miller, I just saw on my bulletin board write a D in this seminar course.

01:59.888 --> 02:00.709
[SPEAKER_01]: He said, yeah, I know.

02:00.729 --> 02:01.550
[SPEAKER_01]: I gave it to you.

02:02.992 --> 02:18.392
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, we were told that if we had our attendance plus our presentation of a program would determine our grade, and we had, and I told him who our speaker was, and he said, yes, I know that too.

02:20.110 --> 02:21.993
[SPEAKER_01]: But he said, actually, you should be flunked.

02:23.936 --> 02:28.183
[SPEAKER_01]: And if you were not a graduating senior with a good record, you would have been flunked.

02:30.246 --> 02:37.116
[SPEAKER_01]: He said, nobody ought to graduate from Texas A&M University with that kind of a presentation of material.

02:40.482 --> 02:43.266
[SPEAKER_01]: So I snuck out of there with my D.

02:45.676 --> 02:48.683
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was mad as it could be.

02:48.703 --> 02:51.068
[SPEAKER_01]: The guy, you know, he was dishonest.

02:51.088 --> 02:56.359
[SPEAKER_01]: There was just nothing was good about the whole situation.

02:58.103 --> 03:04.056
[SPEAKER_01]: Until I got over that and I began to recollect a little and then I began to appreciate what he had told me.

03:05.825 --> 03:21.729
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, as I came back here at school and then on the staff, I learned to appreciate Dr. Jack Miller above most all other people I ever knew in my life.

03:23.171 --> 03:27.177
[SPEAKER_01]: A first-class human being, great teacher.

03:28.398 --> 03:32.845
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, he was head of the department, then dean of agriculture.

03:33.618 --> 03:36.566
[SPEAKER_01]: and one of the real fine people I know.

03:37.730 --> 03:47.357
[SPEAKER_01]: We were at a program together up in Washington State one time, the next time I saw him, and I reminded him of that.

03:48.704 --> 03:50.907
[SPEAKER_01]: He said, yeah, oh, yes, I remember.

03:51.167 --> 03:59.096
[SPEAKER_01]: And then I told it again in front of his wife what a sorry guy he was.

03:59.116 --> 04:06.605
[SPEAKER_01]: No, of course, jokingly, because I say at that time we were very, very close friends, and I had a great respect for them.

04:06.625 --> 04:09.949
[SPEAKER_01]: Anyway, he taught me a lesson is the whole story.

04:10.090 --> 04:13.834
[SPEAKER_01]: He taught me a lesson that I needed to learn.

04:14.725 --> 04:16.648
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's go back to that freshman year.

04:17.730 --> 04:30.470
[SPEAKER_01]: What kind of duties, tasks did a fish have in that boarding house and then over in the project house?

04:31.592 --> 04:37.982
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, in the boarding house we didn't have any particular assigned duties except making a bed or...

04:38.266 --> 04:46.519
[SPEAKER_01]: out sweeping the room of one of the upperclassmen, but it was a very erratic, poorly coordinated situation.

04:46.539 --> 04:52.910
[SPEAKER_01]: It was just who could, which of the upperclassmen could grab you and make you miserable.

04:55.013 --> 04:58.539
[SPEAKER_01]: In the project houses, it was not so much that way.

04:58.579 --> 05:04.408
[SPEAKER_01]: We didn't have many tasks assigned for the upperclassmen.

05:04.388 --> 05:10.754
[SPEAKER_01]: We did our own beds, cleaned our own rooms, and you'd be in a room with upperclassmen.

05:11.194 --> 05:13.196
[SPEAKER_01]: Freshmen and upperclassmen might be in the same room.

05:13.617 --> 05:16.760
[SPEAKER_01]: Was there paddling or anything like that in the project house?

05:16.800 --> 05:18.461
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, some.

05:18.481 --> 05:33.315
[SPEAKER_01]: It was not as bad because in addition to the house weather, you had a sort of a captain in the, I don't know if you could call him a captain, but anyway, a senior upperclassman who pretty well kept

05:34.865 --> 06:00.973
[SPEAKER_01]: kept the thing in and you stayed in the cavalry yes same outfit and some of the other youngsters in that house were in different outfits yes it had no relationship all right you would go over and fall in did you didn't or no you didn't march into breakfast did you no we didn't march into breakfast but we had of course when it was time to

06:01.527 --> 06:01.968
[SPEAKER_01]: Drill.

06:02.608 --> 06:06.152
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, you had an assigned tent, what, two hours for a drill.

06:06.353 --> 06:07.834
[SPEAKER_01]: Where would you fall in for that?

06:08.155 --> 06:09.977
[SPEAKER_01]: Over by Law and Prairie Hall.

06:10.778 --> 06:12.560
[SPEAKER_01]: And then where did y'all usually drill?

06:13.041 --> 06:22.692
[SPEAKER_01]: On the drill field across the street, except in the cavalry we had drilled on horses, and they were out across the

06:23.549 --> 06:26.795
[SPEAKER_01]: railroad tracks in the cavalry stables.

06:26.815 --> 06:30.080
[SPEAKER_01]: All right, describe, I haven't talked to anybody yet from cavalry.

06:30.822 --> 06:37.353
[SPEAKER_01]: How many horses were there and what kind of care did the horses get and so forth?

06:37.373 --> 06:38.956
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know exactly how many.

06:39.016 --> 06:41.701
[SPEAKER_01]: I know they could take an entire troop at one drill.

06:43.083 --> 06:45.928
[SPEAKER_01]: So that would be, I imagine they had

06:47.613 --> 06:52.060
[SPEAKER_01]: Probably at least 50 head, 40 to 50 head of horses.

06:52.681 --> 06:54.223
[SPEAKER_01]: What variety of horses?

06:55.425 --> 07:14.093
[SPEAKER_01]: They were not any particular breed, but the cavalry bought horses from farmers and ranchers all over the country, whether it was in the military, it was here, or for the cavalry units, which were very active then, horse units.

07:14.073 --> 07:17.378
[SPEAKER_01]: were still going on in the regular Army.

07:17.839 --> 07:20.082
[SPEAKER_01]: Were you accustomed to horses before you got here?

07:20.262 --> 07:20.503
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

07:22.085 --> 07:24.008
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, that's one reason I wasn't a cavalry.

07:24.048 --> 07:28.915
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course we didn't have a big ranch, but I was a cowboy.

07:28.935 --> 07:30.157
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, you got to be a cowboy.

07:30.217 --> 07:31.179
[SPEAKER_01]: You're going to be a farmer.

07:32.821 --> 07:41.194
[SPEAKER_01]: So they had a stable hand who took care of the horses.

07:42.524 --> 08:08.953
[SPEAKER_01]: and uh did you have to saddle them and yes we saddled our own horses and we were assigned a horse and you took it whatever it was good bad or indifferent how many how many cadets might have be assigned to the same horse i would say not over four right while one of the others was out on that horse what did you other three do

08:09.220 --> 08:14.930
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, no, we didn't drill at the same, in other words, they would have one cavalry or two cavalry units out there at one time.

08:15.070 --> 08:15.972
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, okay.

08:15.992 --> 08:22.102
[SPEAKER_01]: Then at another time, you would drill the other, the other troop would drill.

08:27.231 --> 08:29.696
[SPEAKER_01]: I think I'm right here, because it's been a long time ago.

08:30.277 --> 08:32.781
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you play polo?

08:33.335 --> 08:39.027
[SPEAKER_01]: I tried, but I couldn't spend the time, which is another story about me having to get a job.

08:40.250 --> 08:48.868
[SPEAKER_01]: I had to give up the idea of playing polo because I got a job so I could stay in school, but that's a different story I'll tell you about in a little while.

08:52.575 --> 08:53.858
[SPEAKER_01]: We did have a...

08:57.145 --> 09:01.830
[SPEAKER_01]: A team, a hunting, jumping team.

09:01.850 --> 09:02.851
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was on to that.

09:03.632 --> 09:11.940
[SPEAKER_01]: We didn't have a lot of competition, but we did have a, go to an event in Austin.

09:13.422 --> 09:18.227
[SPEAKER_01]: They did what the horses, what they called PORTAY, we had trucks that they loaded them in and hauled them.

09:18.908 --> 09:19.688
[SPEAKER_01]: What's the word?

09:20.329 --> 09:20.970
[SPEAKER_01]: PORTAY.

09:21.530 --> 09:22.171
[SPEAKER_01]: PORTAY.

09:22.271 --> 09:23.052
[SPEAKER_01]: How do you spell that?

09:23.492 --> 09:23.973
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know.

09:23.993 --> 09:26.055
[SPEAKER_01]: P-O-R-T.

09:27.503 --> 09:28.786
[SPEAKER_01]: Double E, I think.

09:30.349 --> 09:37.024
[SPEAKER_01]: I guess the French word, I don't know what it is, but that's where you'd load them up and haul them.

09:38.948 --> 09:44.500
[SPEAKER_01]: So we had that contest and some others locally here, other teams that would come in and we would

09:45.425 --> 09:49.230
[SPEAKER_01]: do this hunt course or the jumping courses on that.

09:50.071 --> 09:58.002
[SPEAKER_01]: Did y'all sometimes have cavalry drills on Saturday or was that normally just during the five days?

09:59.423 --> 10:08.215
[SPEAKER_01]: That was mostly during the five days because you had to walk the bull ring on Saturdays if you messed up.

10:08.936 --> 10:13.542
[SPEAKER_01]: No, that was on the afternoons and one of the problems we had was

10:15.530 --> 10:25.266
[SPEAKER_01]: It was in the—it was at the—first thing after lunch was the one—one of the times I had.

10:26.368 --> 10:27.790
[SPEAKER_01]: And remember, it was across the tracks.

10:28.992 --> 10:32.919
[SPEAKER_01]: I had chemistry lab that was from one to three.

10:33.640 --> 10:35.483
[SPEAKER_01]: You had chemistry lab from three to five.

10:36.965 --> 10:39.850
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had a chemistry teacher that would lock you out if you were late.

10:41.180 --> 10:45.005
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes they didn't turn us loose quick enough over there.

10:45.025 --> 10:48.990
[SPEAKER_01]: And we were walking from the railroad tracks to the chemistry building.

10:49.010 --> 10:52.735
[SPEAKER_01]: That didn't happen often, but usually it didn't work, but it did happen.

10:54.097 --> 10:57.481
[SPEAKER_01]: And that was a, that created somewhat of a problem.

10:58.082 --> 11:03.289
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's see, so among the Aggie terminology, you didn't have a fish old lady.

11:04.737 --> 11:05.238
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you?

11:05.418 --> 11:11.788
[SPEAKER_01]: Like they used to, the freshman in the core dorms had a freshman roommate who was his old lady.

11:11.968 --> 11:15.393
[SPEAKER_01]: You didn't have... Not until the next year.

11:15.854 --> 11:16.334
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

11:16.454 --> 11:18.117
[SPEAKER_01]: When I moved into the dormitories.

11:18.858 --> 11:29.975
[SPEAKER_01]: And that first year in the project house, did y'all talk Aggie lingo about the food?

11:30.776 --> 11:32.899
[SPEAKER_01]: Did y'all give it the nicknames and all that?

11:33.119 --> 11:33.580
[SPEAKER_01]: You bet.

11:35.011 --> 11:39.077
[SPEAKER_01]: and the whole bit in that particular respect.

11:39.858 --> 11:44.144
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you get any trouble when you got home and forgot and used some Aggie lingo?

11:46.147 --> 11:47.269
[SPEAKER_01]: Not at home.

11:47.649 --> 12:03.432
[SPEAKER_01]: I did a time or two in mixed company with the nice girls or boys or ladies or somebody else that when it sort of slipped out and you were ashamed of yourself for

12:04.036 --> 12:14.556
[SPEAKER_01]: As that first year developed, what did you learn about what to do in class?

12:15.117 --> 12:20.307
[SPEAKER_01]: What were the rules that you realized about going to class and behavior in class?

12:22.413 --> 12:25.557
[SPEAKER_01]: It was pretty much just cut and dried.

12:25.857 --> 12:37.151
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, you had learned, a lot of us, most of us, in old days, when you grow up during the Depression, there's a lot of things bad, but there's some things that are good, too.

12:37.691 --> 12:46.862
[SPEAKER_01]: You learn discipline in most cases, certainly more so, I think, than maybe you would now.

12:47.804 --> 12:51.508
[SPEAKER_01]: But you learn discipline and you learn respect for authority.

12:54.087 --> 13:02.757
[SPEAKER_01]: And there was not much hesitancy if you misbehaved badly.

13:03.941 --> 13:06.409
[SPEAKER_01]: There was no hesitancy in kicking you out of class.

13:08.431 --> 13:11.115
[SPEAKER_01]: So this pretty well took care of itself.

13:11.436 --> 13:12.718
[SPEAKER_01]: How often did you cut class?

13:13.559 --> 13:14.120
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't cut.

13:14.320 --> 13:16.364
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't cut class without an excuse.

13:16.945 --> 13:22.193
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm talking about a good, without a reason, a good reason.

13:22.233 --> 13:23.134
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't cut class.

13:23.215 --> 13:27.241
[SPEAKER_01]: I couldn't afford to because I wasn't that great a student.

13:28.263 --> 13:28.463
[SPEAKER_01]: All right.

13:28.483 --> 13:32.389
[SPEAKER_01]: And then in class, did you stay awake?

13:32.409 --> 13:32.970
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

13:34.148 --> 13:45.139
[SPEAKER_01]: By and large, I'm sure I dozed at times, but I recall one kid in class that had a very propensity to doze off, and this was in military science.

13:47.402 --> 13:54.870
[SPEAKER_01]: And so he, we had this military science book, what we called a bullet text, was about yea thick.

13:56.551 --> 13:57.712
[SPEAKER_01]: And this kid went to sleep.

13:59.815 --> 14:03.058
[SPEAKER_01]: Instructor took that book, bullet text book, big old book,

14:04.034 --> 14:16.193
[SPEAKER_01]: walked around very quietly, and right by the side of him, the kid there all humped over and right by the side of him, he slammed that book on the floor, and it popped like a shotgun went off, and that kid almost climbed clear to the ceiling.

14:17.655 --> 14:32.218
[SPEAKER_01]: So we, yeah, we stayed awake pretty much because I'd say in my case, this wasn't, many of us, we had to because we needed to learn all we could because we knew the test was coming sooner than later.

14:33.650 --> 14:51.554
[SPEAKER_01]: I had, in this project house deal, and one of my things that might be interesting, hopefully, as I said earlier, I knew I had to work, and I came up Thanksgiving, almost Thanksgiving, I didn't have a job.

14:51.614 --> 14:52.575
[SPEAKER_01]: I'd applied everywhere.

14:53.536 --> 14:57.962
[SPEAKER_01]: Stores, mess hall, everywhere you could.

14:58.463 --> 15:03.049
[SPEAKER_01]: And also, I'd applied in the animal science department for a job anywhere.

15:03.738 --> 15:06.542
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, in stables, had horses, had cattle.

15:08.024 --> 15:12.871
[SPEAKER_01]: So came Thanksgiving time and I didn't have a job.

15:12.911 --> 15:13.772
[SPEAKER_01]: I was pretty desperate.

15:15.435 --> 15:23.326
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, again, I was going to meet my folks at my sister's for Thanksgiving instead of going home.

15:25.369 --> 15:26.691
[SPEAKER_01]: I packed my suitcase.

15:28.257 --> 15:30.541
[SPEAKER_01]: picked it up and started out of the room.

15:31.042 --> 15:32.845
[SPEAKER_01]: And about that time a knock came on the door.

15:34.849 --> 15:46.350
[SPEAKER_01]: And Rudy Rader, Vaughn Rader at that time, who was an animal science teacher, was standing there and he was in charge of the beef cattle center and the beef cattle herd.

15:49.115 --> 15:57.003
[SPEAKER_01]: He said, you applied for a job in animal science, I mean down in the animal and beef cattle center, right?

15:57.504 --> 15:58.145
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, yes, sir.

16:00.387 --> 16:04.872
[SPEAKER_01]: He said, do you want to work bad enough to unpack that suitcase and be down there in 30 minutes?

16:06.333 --> 16:07.014
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, yes, sir.

16:08.335 --> 16:12.300
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't stutter, stammer, or worry about Thanksgiving.

16:12.320 --> 16:14.582
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, I'd been away from home all that time too.

16:16.790 --> 16:19.094
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's how I got my first job.

16:19.594 --> 16:20.796
[SPEAKER_01]: Do you remember what the pay was?

16:20.936 --> 16:21.657
[SPEAKER_01]: Exactly.

16:22.018 --> 16:25.764
[SPEAKER_01]: Twenty-five cents an hour, and I was glad to get that sucker.

16:25.784 --> 16:28.087
[SPEAKER_01]: And about how many hours a week?

16:28.107 --> 16:28.588
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

16:29.289 --> 16:35.018
[SPEAKER_01]: I probably worked about 20 hours a week or more.

16:35.757 --> 16:36.618
[SPEAKER_01]: What were the duties?

16:37.138 --> 16:40.042
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, cleaning out cow stalls.

16:40.062 --> 16:43.585
[SPEAKER_01]: And we had a herd of, we had show cattle that time.

16:44.186 --> 16:47.770
[SPEAKER_01]: A small segment of it was show cattle.

16:47.790 --> 16:48.831
[SPEAKER_01]: So we had nurse cows.

16:50.913 --> 16:58.541
[SPEAKER_01]: So we'd bring those nurse cows in out of the pasture, which we'd have to round up riding an old high-headed horse that didn't watch for the potholes.

16:59.823 --> 17:02.185
[SPEAKER_01]: We'd get those cows in there every morning.

17:04.568 --> 17:04.768
[SPEAKER_01]: Excuse me.

17:06.571 --> 17:12.940
[SPEAKER_01]: and then turn those calves in and let them nurse these cows.

17:12.960 --> 17:13.862
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, that was the job.

17:15.504 --> 17:19.650
[SPEAKER_01]: Then we cleaned out stalls every two or three days, but particularly Saturday.

17:19.710 --> 17:21.312
[SPEAKER_01]: Worked nearly all day Saturday.

17:22.234 --> 17:26.520
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, you still had your Sunday chores to do, morning and night.

17:26.939 --> 17:36.168
[SPEAKER_01]: So living in a project house, and at that time the Beef Kettle Center was over here where the computer science area is, that old pavilion.

17:37.890 --> 17:49.281
[SPEAKER_01]: Pasture was out on what's now the golf course, and so we had to get up early.

17:49.341 --> 17:53.925
[SPEAKER_01]: I usually get up around 5 o'clock, 5.30, and be down, I had to be down at the barns.

17:54.361 --> 18:02.248
[SPEAKER_01]: about 6, 6.15 in order to get all those chores done, get back, get breakfast, and get to an 8 o'clock class.

18:03.389 --> 18:08.573
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'd spend an hour or more down here, but it was a tight schedule.

18:09.974 --> 18:17.621
[SPEAKER_01]: So I hitchhiked to Bryan and bought a bicycle so I could get there quicker and get back quicker.

18:19.423 --> 18:21.284
[SPEAKER_01]: And I still remember how much I paid for it.

18:21.324 --> 18:23.406
[SPEAKER_01]: I paid $6 for that sucker.

18:23.960 --> 18:27.704
[SPEAKER_01]: And it had all the wheels, tires, and no bells or anything.

18:29.366 --> 18:31.428
[SPEAKER_01]: So I rode that bicycle then.

18:31.448 --> 18:35.893
[SPEAKER_01]: So you kept it at the project house and rode it.

18:36.514 --> 18:38.196
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you ride it to class also?

18:38.236 --> 18:41.720
[SPEAKER_01]: No, very seldom, if I didn't have to.

18:41.860 --> 18:43.281
[SPEAKER_01]: You rode it to work and back.

18:43.321 --> 18:47.326
[SPEAKER_01]: Right, I rode to work and back, unless something was way off on the other side of the campus.

18:47.346 --> 18:49.208
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't because...

18:49.188 --> 18:53.855
[SPEAKER_01]: There was very little stuff stolen on this campus in those years.

18:54.335 --> 18:56.739
[SPEAKER_01]: Very, very seldom.

18:56.759 --> 18:58.021
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you lock it always?

18:58.241 --> 18:58.842
[SPEAKER_01]: No, never.

18:59.623 --> 19:01.446
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't know what locking a bicycle was.

19:03.108 --> 19:14.845
[SPEAKER_01]: In the dormitories, for this point, there were people who would have a candy concession in the dormitories.

19:15.386 --> 19:18.891
[SPEAKER_01]: And that candy was out in the hallway, wide open in boxes.

19:20.305 --> 19:27.475
[SPEAKER_01]: And you took a piece of candy and put your nickel or dime in this money box, wide open money box.

19:29.578 --> 19:36.267
[SPEAKER_01]: And it was very, very seldom that any of that stuff, money or candy, was taken.

19:37.549 --> 19:38.891
[SPEAKER_01]: Can you believe that?

19:40.012 --> 19:40.733
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a hard one.

19:40.753 --> 19:41.034
[SPEAKER_01]: All right.

19:41.074 --> 19:44.278
[SPEAKER_01]: So you didn't go home until Christmas, your first semester?

19:44.479 --> 19:44.719
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

19:45.540 --> 19:46.241
[SPEAKER_01]: How did you get home?

19:47.002 --> 19:47.543
[SPEAKER_01]: Hitchhiking.

19:48.164 --> 19:49.165
[SPEAKER_01]: How long did it take?

